{"title_page": "Madame Bey", "text_new": "{{short description|American operator of a boxing camp}}\n{{Ottoman Turkish name|Hranoush||Agaganian}}\n[[File:Beyyoung.jpg|thumb|Madame Bey in DC]]\n'''Hranoush Sidky Bey''' (circa 1881 \u2013 January 30, 1942), better known as '''Madame Bey''', ran a boxing camp for world champion boxers in [[Chatham Township, New Jersey]], in the United States. Her life and boxing camp are documented in the book ''Madame Bey's: Home to Boxing Legends''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pantalone|first1=Gene|title=Madame Bey's; Home to Boxing Legends|url=http://bookstore.archwaypublishing.com/Products/SKU-001044096/Madame-Beys-Home-to-Boxing-Legends.aspx|website=Madame Bey's: Home to Boxing Legends|publisher=Archway Publishing|accessdate=2 October 2016}}</ref> Her prominence during the time she operated her boxing camp from 1923\u20131942 is documented in the thousands of press photos taken at her camp.<ref>{{cite web|title=Madame Bey|url=https://www.facebook.com/MadameBey|website=Madame Bey Facebook Page|accessdate=12 July 2016}}</ref> Forgotten today, her camp's namesake was an everyday occurrence in sports sections of newspapers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Search over 35,875,000 Historical Newspaper Pages from the USA & Canada|url=http://www.fultonhistory.com/Fulton.html|website=Old Fulton Post Cards|publisher=Fulton History|accessdate=14 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nMadame Bey was born '''Hranoush Agaganian''',<ref name=Hageman>{{cite web|author=Hageman, Robert A.|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050311202959/http://summitnjhistory.org/Historian_MadamBey.php|title=Madam Bey's - Training Camp for Champion prizefighters|publisher=The Summit Historical Society|location=[[Summit, New Jersey]]|accessdate=2019-06-27}}</ref> in [[Ottoman Constantinople|Constantinople]] (now [[Istanbul]]), [[Ottoman Empire]].{{fact|date=June 2019}} Her parents were Armenian and French.<ref name=Hageman/> She attended American College,<ref name=Hageman/> a.k.a. Constantinople College for Girls (now a part of [[Robert College]]),<ref name=Kuneralpp103>Kuneralp, Sinan. \"Ottoman Diplomatic and Consular Personnel in the United States of America, 1867\u20131917.\" In: Criss, Nur Bilge, Sel\u00e7uk Esenbel, Tony Greenwood, and Louis Mazzari (editors). ''American Turkish Encounters: Politics and Culture, 1830\u20131989'' ([[EBSCO]] Ebook Academic Collection). [[Cambridge Scholars Publishing]], 12 July 2011. {{ISBN|144383260X}}, 9781443832601. pp. [https://books.google.com/books?id=FBcrBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA100 100]-[https://books.google.com/books?id=FBcrBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA108 108]. CITED: p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=FBcrBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA103 103].</ref> in Constantinople. Her family opposed her marriage to the Turkish Muslim Sidki Bey, who joined the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Ottoman Empire)|Ottoman Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] and took a posting in Washington and later in New York. Her husband resigned from his position when the Ottoman government asked him to go to Berlin and the two remained stateside.<ref name=Hageman/>\n\nShe was educated, a mother, a mezzo-soprano opera singer, wife of a Turkish diplomat, and personified sophistication during her years in Washington, D. C. President [[William McKinley]] and his wife considered her a friend and she was a few feet away when McKinley was assassinated.<ref>{{cite news|title=Madame Bey Dies; Ran Training Camp|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19420131&id=NQgrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LZkFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2901,5430754&hl=en|accessdate=14 July 2016|agency=Associated Press|publisher=Montreal Gazette|date=31 January 1942}}</ref> When renowned journalist [[Damon Runyon]] visited the camp to watch [[Max Schmeling]], Runyon wrote, \"With Max Schmeling and his training we have no concern here. Our concern is with Madame Bey, the lady who runs the place known as Madame Bey's, a famous training camp for prize fighters.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Runyon|first1=Damon|title=The Brighter Side of the News|agency=Kings Feature Syndicate|publisher=Times-Union, Albany, N.Y.|date=24 November 1937}}</ref> She created a home for her boxing clientele in which they could train for their sport. The boxers who stayed at her boxing camp, followed her rules that she expected her boarders to obey. There was no alcohol; up by six; breakfast at seven; supper at five; lights out at ten; no swearing; and no women. She was strict in running her business but had personal, matriarchal relationships with her boxers. She called them her boys. She spoke seven languages \u2013 English, Armenian, French, German, Greek, Italian, and Spanish. She ran a successful Oriental rug business with her husband after they left the diplomatic corps, but her boxing endeavor she coveted the most.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hageman|first1=Robert|title=Madam Bey's \u2013 Training Camp for Champion Prizefighters|url=http://www.summithistoricalsociety.com/historian/2016/3/26/madam-beys-training-camp-for-champion-prizefighters|website=The Summit Historical Society|publisher=The Summit Historical Society|accessdate=12 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nAmong her favorite fighters were [[Max Schmeling]], [[Freddie Steele]], [[Tommy Farr]], [[Paul Berlenbach]], [[Primo Carnera]], [[Lou Ambers]], and [[Gene Tunney]], whom she called her \"polished emerald.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Madame Bey Dies At Morristown|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1913&dat=19420130&id=W6g0AAAAIBAJ&sjid=32kFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4420,2299205&hl=en|accessdate=12 July 2016|publisher=Associated Press|date=30 January 1942}}</ref> According to ''Madame Bey's: Home to Boxing Legends'', the following is an alphabetic list of people associated with boxing that were in Chatham Township, New Jersey, where Madame Bey's camp resided. [[Georgie Abrams]], [[Lou Ambers]], [[Fred Apostoli]], [[Red Applegate]], [[Ray Arcel]], Freddie Archer, [[Henry Armstrong]], [[Buddy Baer]], [[Max Baer (boxer)|Max Baer]], [[Joe Baksi]], Sam Baroudi, Billy Beauhuld, [[Tommy Bell (boxer)|Tommy Bell]], Steve Belloise, [[Paul Berlenbach]], [[Melio Bettina]], Carmine Bilotti, [[Whitey Bimstein]], [[Jimmy Bivins]], [[James J. Braddock|James Braddock]], Jorge Brescia, [[Jack Britton]], [[Fred Brown (boxer)|Freddy Brown]], Al Buck, [[Red Burman]], [[Mushy Callahan]], Victor Campolo, [[Tony Canzoneri]], [[Primo Carnera]], [[Georges Carpentier]], Jimmy Carter, [[Rubin Carter]], [[Ezzard Charles]], [[Kid Chocolate]], [[Gil Clancy]], [[Freddie Cochrane]], Jimmy Carrollo, [[James J. Corbett]], Lulu Costantino, Cus D\u2019Amato, [[Jack Delaney]], Al Davis, Red Top Davis, James P. Dawson, [[Jack Dempsey]], Gus Dorazio, Carl Duane, Chris Dundee, [[Johnny Dundee]], [[Vince Dundee]], [[Sixto Escobar]], [[Tommy Farr]], Abe Feldman, Freddie Fiducia, [[Jackie Fields]], [[F. Scott Fitzgerald]], [[Billy Fox (boxer)|Billy Fox]], [[Humbert Fugazy]], [[Charley Fusari]] , [[Tony Galento]], [[Kid Gavil\u00e1n]], [[Frankie Genaro]], [[Billy Gibson (boxing)|Billy Gibson]], [[Joey Giardello]], [[George Godfrey (boxer born 1897)|George Godfrey]], [[Arturo Godoy]], [[Charley Goldman]], [[Ruby Goldstein]], [[Bud Gorman]], [[Billy Graham]], [[Frank Graham (boxer)|Frank Graham]], [[Rocky Graziano]], Abe Greene, [[Gus Greenlee]], [[Emile Griffith]], [[Babe Herman]], Steve Hostak, Ace Hudkins, Herbert Hype Igoe, [[Beau Jack]], [[Tommy Hurricane Jackson]], [[Jimmy Jacobs]], [[Joe Jacobs (boxer)|Joe Jacobs]], [[Mike Jacobs (boxing)|Mike Jacobs]], [[Joe Jeanette]], [[Ben Jeby]], [[Lew Jenkins]], [[Jack Johnson (boxer)|Jack Johnson]],  [[James Johnston (boxer)|James Johnston]], [[Doug Jones (boxer)|Doug Jones]], Ralph Tiger Jones, Phil Kaplan, [[Jack Kearns]], Frankie Klick, [[Johnny Kilbane]], [[Solly Krieger]], [[Jake LaMotta]], [[Tippy Larkin]], [[Benny Leonard]], [[Gus Lesnevich]], [[King Levinsky]], [[John Henry Lewis]], Isaac Logart, [[Tommy Loughran]], [[Joe Louis]], [[Joe Lynch (boxer)|Joe Lynch]], Eddie Mader, Nathan Mann, [[Rocky Marciano]], [[Lloyd Marshall]], [[Eddie Martin (boxer)|Eddie Martin]], [[Bat Masterson]],  [[Joey Maxim]], [[Jimmy McLarnin]], [[Mike McTigue]], Jack Miley, [[Bob Montgomery (boxer)|Bob Montgomery]], [[Archie Moore]], [[Tod Morgan]], [[Dan Morgan]], [[Walter Neusel]], [[Kid Norfolk]], [[Lou Nova]], Jack O\u2019Brien, [[Bob Olin]], Lee Oma, [[Carlos Ortiz]], [[Ken Overlin]], [[Benny Kid Paret]], [[Floyd Patterson]], [[Willie Pep]], [[Billy Petrolle]], Willie Ratner, [[Grantland Rice]], Gilbert Rogin, [[Maxie Rosenbloom]], Al Roth, [[Andre Routis]], Irving Rudd, Bobby Ruffin, [[Damon Runyon]], [[Sandy Saddler]], [[Lou Salica]], [[Johnny Saxton]], [[Max Schmeling]], Flashy Sebastian, [[Marty Servo]], [[Jack Sharkey]], [[Battling Siki]], [[Eric Seelig]], [[Freddie Steele]], Allie Stolz, [[Young Stribling]], [[Herman Taylor (boxing)|Herman Taylor]], [[Lew Tendler]], [[Sid Terris]], Young Terry, [[Jack Thompson (boxer)|Jack Thompson]], [[Jose Torres (boxer)|Jose Torres]], [[Gene Tunney]], [[Pancho Villa]], [[Mickey Walker (boxer)|Mickey Walker]], Max Waxman, [[Al Weill]], Charlie Weinert, [[Freddie Welsh]], [[Harry Wills]], [[Charley White]], [[Johnny Wilson (boxer)|Johnny Wilson]], [[Chalky Wright]], [[Paulino Uzcudun]], [[Jersey Joe Walcott]], [[Ike Williams]], [[Teddy Yarosz]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pantalone|first1=Gene|title=Madame Bey's: Home to Boxing Legends|url=http://bookstore.archwaypublishing.com/Products/SKU-001044096/Madame-Beys-Home-to-Boxing-Legends.aspx|website=Madame Bey's: Home to Boxing Legends|publisher=Archway Publishing|accessdate=2 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* ''Turkish Diplomatic Life in Washington, Under the Old Regime''. Cochrane Publishing Company, [[New York Tribune Building|Tribune Building]], 1910. - Bey anonymously published this work<ref name=Kuneralpp103/> - [https://books.google.com/books/about/Turkish_Diplomatic_Life_in_Washington_Un.html?id=MnPStAEACAAJ&redir_esc=y Google Books profile]\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ottoman Armenians]]\n* [[Ottoman Empire-United States relations]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bey, Madame}}\n[[Category:1880s births]]\n[[Category:1942 deaths]]\n[[Category:Boxing trainers]]\n[[Category:Armenian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:People from Chatham Township, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Armenians of the Ottoman Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American operator of a boxing camp}}\n{{Ottoman Turkish name|Hranoush||Agaganian}}\n[[File:Beyyoung.jpg|thumb|Madame Bey in DC]]\n'''Hranoush Sidky Bey''' (circa 1881 \u2013 January 30, 1942), better known as '''Madame Bey''', ran a boxing camp for world champion boxers in [[Chatham Township, New Jersey]], in the United States. Her life and boxing camp are documented in the book ''Madame Bey's: Home to Boxing Legends''.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pantalone|first1=Gene|title=Madame Bey's; Home to Boxing Legends|url=http://bookstore.archwaypublishing.com/Products/SKU-001044096/Madame-Beys-Home-to-Boxing-Legends.aspx|website=Madame Bey's: Home to Boxing Legends|publisher=Archway Publishing|accessdate=2 October 2016}}</ref> Her prominence during the time she operated her boxing camp from 1923\u20131942 is documented in the thousands of press photos taken at her camp.<ref>{{cite web|title=Madame Bey|url=https://www.facebook.com/MadameBey|website=Madame Bey Facebook Page|accessdate=12 July 2016}}</ref> Forgotten today, her camp's namesake was an everyday occurrence in sports sections of newspapers.<ref>{{cite web|title=Search over 35,875,000 Historical Newspaper Pages from the USA & Canada|url=http://www.fultonhistory.com/Fulton.html|website=Old Fulton Post Cards|publisher=Fulton History|accessdate=14 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nMadame Bey was born '''Hranoush Agaganian''',<ref name=Hageman>{{cite web|author=Hageman, Robert A.|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050311202959/http://summitnjhistory.org/Historian_MadamBey.php|title=Madam Bey's - Training Camp for Champion prizefighters|publisher=The Summit Historical Society|location=[[Summit, New Jersey]]|accessdate=2019-06-27}}</ref> in [[Constantinople]] ([[Istanbul]]), [[Ottoman Empire]].{{fact|date=June 2019}} Her parents were Armenian and French.<ref name=Hageman/> She attended American College,<ref name=Hageman/> a.k.a. Constantinople College for Girls (now a part of [[Robert College]]),<ref name=Kuneralpp103>Kuneralp, Sinan. \"Ottoman Diplomatic and Consular Personnel in the United States of America, 1867\u20131917.\" In: Criss, Nur Bilge, Sel\u00e7uk Esenbel, Tony Greenwood, and Louis Mazzari (editors). ''American Turkish Encounters: Politics and Culture, 1830\u20131989'' ([[EBSCO]] Ebook Academic Collection). [[Cambridge Scholars Publishing]], 12 July 2011. {{ISBN|144383260X}}, 9781443832601. pp. [https://books.google.com/books?id=FBcrBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA100 100]-[https://books.google.com/books?id=FBcrBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA108 108]. CITED: p. [https://books.google.com/books?id=FBcrBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA103 103].</ref> in Constantinople. Her family opposed her marriage to the Turkish Muslim Sidki Bey, who joined the [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Ottoman Empire)|Ottoman Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] and took a posting in Washington and later in New York. Her husband resigned from his position when the Ottoman government asked him to go to Berlin and the two remained stateside.<ref name=Hageman/>\n\nShe was educated, a mother, a mezzo-soprano opera singer, wife of a Turkish diplomat, and personified sophistication during her years in Washington, D. C. President [[William McKinley]] and his wife considered her a friend and she was a few feet away when McKinley was assassinated.<ref>{{cite news|title=Madame Bey Dies; Ran Training Camp|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1946&dat=19420131&id=NQgrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LZkFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2901,5430754&hl=en|accessdate=14 July 2016|agency=Associated Press|publisher=Montreal Gazette|date=31 January 1942}}</ref> When renowned journalist [[Damon Runyon]] visited the camp to watch [[Max Schmeling]], Runyon wrote, \"With Max Schmeling and his training we have no concern here. Our concern is with Madame Bey, the lady who runs the place known as Madame Bey's, a famous training camp for prize fighters.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Runyon|first1=Damon|title=The Brighter Side of the News|agency=Kings Feature Syndicate|publisher=Times-Union, Albany, N.Y.|date=24 November 1937}}</ref> She created a home for her boxing clientele in which they could train for their sport. The boxers who stayed at her boxing camp, followed her rules that she expected her boarders to obey. There was no alcohol; up by six; breakfast at seven; supper at five; lights out at ten; no swearing; and no women. She was strict in running her business but had personal, matriarchal relationships with her boxers. She called them her boys. She spoke seven languages \u2013 English, Armenian, French, German, Greek, Italian, and Spanish. She ran a successful Oriental rug business with her husband after they left the diplomatic corps, but her boxing endeavor she coveted the most.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hageman|first1=Robert|title=Madam Bey's \u2013 Training Camp for Champion Prizefighters|url=http://www.summithistoricalsociety.com/historian/2016/3/26/madam-beys-training-camp-for-champion-prizefighters|website=The Summit Historical Society|publisher=The Summit Historical Society|accessdate=12 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nAmong her favorite fighters were [[Max Schmeling]], [[Freddie Steele]], [[Tommy Farr]], [[Paul Berlenbach]], [[Primo Carnera]], [[Lou Ambers]], and [[Gene Tunney]], whom she called her \"polished emerald.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Madame Bey Dies At Morristown|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1913&dat=19420130&id=W6g0AAAAIBAJ&sjid=32kFAAAAIBAJ&pg=4420,2299205&hl=en|accessdate=12 July 2016|publisher=Associated Press|date=30 January 1942}}</ref> According to ''Madame Bey's: Home to Boxing Legends'', the following is an alphabetic list of people associated with boxing that were in Chatham Township, New Jersey, where Madame Bey's camp resided. [[Georgie Abrams]], [[Lou Ambers]], [[Fred Apostoli]], [[Red Applegate]], [[Ray Arcel]], Freddie Archer, [[Henry Armstrong]], [[Buddy Baer]], [[Max Baer (boxer)|Max Baer]], [[Joe Baksi]], Sam Baroudi, Billy Beauhuld, [[Tommy Bell (boxer)|Tommy Bell]], Steve Belloise, [[Paul Berlenbach]], [[Melio Bettina]], Carmine Bilotti, [[Whitey Bimstein]], [[Jimmy Bivins]], [[James J. Braddock|James Braddock]], Jorge Brescia, [[Jack Britton]], [[Fred Brown (boxer)|Freddy Brown]], Al Buck, [[Red Burman]], [[Mushy Callahan]], Victor Campolo, [[Tony Canzoneri]], [[Primo Carnera]], [[Georges Carpentier]], Jimmy Carter, [[Rubin Carter]], [[Ezzard Charles]], [[Kid Chocolate]], [[Gil Clancy]], [[Freddie Cochrane]], Jimmy Carrollo, [[James J. Corbett]], Lulu Costantino, Cus D\u2019Amato, [[Jack Delaney]], Al Davis, Red Top Davis, James P. Dawson, [[Jack Dempsey]], Gus Dorazio, Carl Duane, Chris Dundee, [[Johnny Dundee]], [[Vince Dundee]], [[Sixto Escobar]], [[Tommy Farr]], Abe Feldman, Freddie Fiducia, [[Jackie Fields]], [[F. Scott Fitzgerald]], [[Billy Fox (boxer)|Billy Fox]], [[Humbert Fugazy]], [[Charley Fusari]] , [[Tony Galento]], [[Kid Gavil\u00e1n]], [[Frankie Genaro]], [[Billy Gibson (boxing)|Billy Gibson]], [[Joey Giardello]], [[George Godfrey (boxer born 1897)|George Godfrey]], [[Arturo Godoy]], [[Charley Goldman]], [[Ruby Goldstein]], [[Bud Gorman]], [[Billy Graham]], [[Frank Graham (boxer)|Frank Graham]], [[Rocky Graziano]], Abe Greene, [[Gus Greenlee]], [[Emile Griffith]], [[Babe Herman]], Steve Hostak, Ace Hudkins, Herbert Hype Igoe, [[Beau Jack]], [[Tommy Hurricane Jackson]], [[Jimmy Jacobs]], [[Joe Jacobs (boxer)|Joe Jacobs]], [[Mike Jacobs (boxing)|Mike Jacobs]], [[Joe Jeanette]], [[Ben Jeby]], [[Lew Jenkins]], [[Jack Johnson (boxer)|Jack Johnson]],  [[James Johnston (boxer)|James Johnston]], [[Doug Jones (boxer)|Doug Jones]], Ralph Tiger Jones, Phil Kaplan, [[Jack Kearns]], Frankie Klick, [[Johnny Kilbane]], [[Solly Krieger]], [[Jake LaMotta]], [[Tippy Larkin]], [[Benny Leonard]], [[Gus Lesnevich]], [[King Levinsky]], [[John Henry Lewis]], Isaac Logart, [[Tommy Loughran]], [[Joe Louis]], [[Joe Lynch (boxer)|Joe Lynch]], Eddie Mader, Nathan Mann, [[Rocky Marciano]], [[Lloyd Marshall]], [[Eddie Martin (boxer)|Eddie Martin]], [[Bat Masterson]],  [[Joey Maxim]], [[Jimmy McLarnin]], [[Mike McTigue]], Jack Miley, [[Bob Montgomery (boxer)|Bob Montgomery]], [[Archie Moore]], [[Tod Morgan]], [[Dan Morgan]], [[Walter Neusel]], [[Kid Norfolk]], [[Lou Nova]], Jack O\u2019Brien, [[Bob Olin]], Lee Oma, [[Carlos Ortiz]], [[Ken Overlin]], [[Benny Kid Paret]], [[Floyd Patterson]], [[Willie Pep]], [[Billy Petrolle]], Willie Ratner, [[Grantland Rice]], Gilbert Rogin, [[Maxie Rosenbloom]], Al Roth, [[Andre Routis]], Irving Rudd, Bobby Ruffin, [[Damon Runyon]], [[Sandy Saddler]], [[Lou Salica]], [[Johnny Saxton]], [[Max Schmeling]], Flashy Sebastian, [[Marty Servo]], [[Jack Sharkey]], [[Battling Siki]], [[Eric Seelig]], [[Freddie Steele]], Allie Stolz, [[Young Stribling]], [[Herman Taylor (boxing)|Herman Taylor]], [[Lew Tendler]], [[Sid Terris]], Young Terry, [[Jack Thompson (boxer)|Jack Thompson]], [[Jose Torres (boxer)|Jose Torres]], [[Gene Tunney]], [[Pancho Villa]], [[Mickey Walker (boxer)|Mickey Walker]], Max Waxman, [[Al Weill]], Charlie Weinert, [[Freddie Welsh]], [[Harry Wills]], [[Charley White]], [[Johnny Wilson (boxer)|Johnny Wilson]], [[Chalky Wright]], [[Paulino Uzcudun]], [[Jersey Joe Walcott]], [[Ike Williams]], [[Teddy Yarosz]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pantalone|first1=Gene|title=Madame Bey's: Home to Boxing Legends|url=http://bookstore.archwaypublishing.com/Products/SKU-001044096/Madame-Beys-Home-to-Boxing-Legends.aspx|website=Madame Bey's: Home to Boxing Legends|publisher=Archway Publishing|accessdate=2 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* ''Turkish Diplomatic Life in Washington, Under the Old Regime''. Cochrane Publishing Company, [[New York Tribune Building|Tribune Building]], 1910. - Bey anonymously published this work<ref name=Kun